Subject: Re: TUMS-10 bug report (v34 of 09-MAY-85) 
In-reply-to: your message of Thu, 16 May 85 0:42:31 PDT

^P and ^N (^J) move you through the current set (CSET or $).  This is
always destroyed by leaving TUMS.  If you have not done a READ command,
^N will do one for you ... READ UNREAD.  If you have done a READ command,
it will go to the next message - of which there might not be any.  So,
basically, NEXT is
	if length(CSET)=0 and no!read!command!yet
		then do!command("READ UNREAD")
		else print!message( CSET[listx(CSET,CMSG,1)] );

This will explain the appearently inconsistent results.  It appears to
take you to where you left off, because CMSG would point to the last
read message before you quit, and ^N (^J) would do a READ UNREAD when
you went back in causing the first unread message to be displayed.

I do agree that things get screwed up when you do an EXPUNGE in that
the CSET and CMSG will still point to the same message numbers, even
though the messages have moved.  I plan to fix this so the CSET and
CMSG will move with the messages.

Other than this, I don't see any inconsistent or incorrect behavoir,
but feel free to point out (or re-point out in different way) anything
you think should be different.

-Bill
